target_title: window-list: Add attention indicator

note.body:
Good question. I tend towards no, unless there's a better option than the label:
 - the hint is used to request attention, so it doesn't work well if you have to actively keynav to the item to notice it
 - if the window is unfocused, gnome-shell handles the hints by showing a notification ("app is ready") which as far as I know works better for a11y
 - the hints are fairly legacy: the API only exists on X11, and apps have been encouraged to use notifications instead for nearly 20 years (telling the user *what* happened is simply much more expressive than indicating that *something* happened)
 - I'm not sure what kind of label would work well with free-form window titles; something like "*" is already used frequently to indicate something else like unsaved changes, and I don't think the following works too well either: `window "window-list: Add attention indicator (!366) · Merge requests · GNOME / gnome-shell-extensions · GitLab" requests your attention`

But if you think it would still be helpful, we can add something.

Window list doesn't dismiss when overview is brought up by tackpad gestures

note.body:
OK, with some strategically placed overrides I've been able to figure it out:
```
Dec 03 11:52:29 silbersee gnome-shell[399363]: Trace
                                               show@file:///usr/share/gnome-shell/extensions/window-list@gnome-shell-extensions.gcampax.github.com/extension.js:1003:17
                                               set visible@file:///usr/share/gnome-shell/extensions/window-list@gnome-shell-extensions.gcampax.github.com/extension.js:997:18
                                               _updateActorVisibility@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/layout.js:975:1
                                               _updateVisibility@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/layout.js:984:29
                                               showOverview@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/layout.js:367:14
                                               _gestureUpdate@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/overview.js:372:32
                                               _updateGesture@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/swipeTracker.js:666:14
                                               _handleEvent@resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/swipeTracker.js:191:18
                                               @resource:///org/gnome/shell/ui/init.js:21:20
```

The window list is set up to track the monitor's fullscreen state, and if the shell updates the visibility after we start entering the overview, it re-shows the window list.

I'll open a MR with the fix.

note.body:
Can you split the commits logically? Like "remove use-more-space setting", "change layout algorithm to ..." etc.

I inherited the extension more than ten years ago, and never used it myself (except for testing). To be honest, I never really got the point of it - it always looked much messier to me than the shell's built-in layout (probably unsurprising, given that I'm primarily a gnome-shell developer).

That doesn't matter too much while just adjusting the extension to shell changes to keep it working, but it makes it harder to review proposed layout changes. Having a logically split commit series with good commit messages[^0] that explain the rationale behind each individual change would help significantly with that.

I will put it in my review queue anyway, but it may take a while ...

[^0]: we have [some guidance](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-shell/-/blob/main/docs/commit-messages.md?ref_type=heads) in the gnome-shell repo

note.body:
Hope this attachment is suitable for you. [stack_trace.txt](/uploads/e4d93a9804d5757f7916543c321d7c05/stack_trace.txt) This came from a fresh install of Ubuntu 24.10 running in a Virtualbox VM.

You will notice that an invalid(?) pointer was encountered in st_theme_resolve_url() after calling g_hash_table_lookup() after which a null return is not checked for (I expect assertions are disabled). 

My suspicion is that the failure when returning from the lock screen is just an artifact on an earlier failure when entering the lock screen. Good luck!

If you forgive the following rant (of course this rant is not aimed at you) from a 74yo who left behind the hideous imperfections of the C programming language so many years ago I cannot remember. 

First the issue of assertions, preconditions, postconditions, etc being removed at production time. This failure no doubt has passed through a series tests that could have identified the original source of the crash. By burying our heads in the sand pretending that an uncontrolled crash is better than controlled exit we are making reliable software more difficult to achieve. I know Linus doesn't agree.

note.body:
> I'd still be interested in making the drop target more visible

I'll leave that to @jimmac :-)

> I've noticed that when you're moving the drag target, the window buttons don't always slide as they move to make space for the drop target

That's copied from the dash behavior. There are two issues:
  - multiple concurrent placeholder animations can make the whole list appear a bit jiggly
  - ongoing animations can lead to unwanted drop position changes, including loops (for example: hovering over position 2, the appearing placeholder changes that to 3, the disappearing placeholder changes it back to 2, ...)

I pushed an update that tries to avoid both issues. I'm quite happy with that, let me know what you think.

note.body:
I tried the latest version of the extension and the addition of the drop target indicator is a big improvement. I would suggest making it visually stronger - maybe increase the lightness and the border width. @jimmac might be able to advise.

Regarding the transparency, I think it does help, but @jimmac is right about the style and we could run into issues with legibility. The challenge with making the drag object smaller ([as suggested above](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-shell-extensions/-/merge_requests/338#note_2238560)) is that the apparent sudden transformation of the object from one size to another would be jarring.

We could alleviate this by transitioning the appearance of the drag object from its original form to a smaller placeholder shape, perhaps which would look like this:

![rect331](/uploads/65837c51be09bd98921b9ecc3e3305c8/rect331.png)

You can see how Google Drive does this for example:

![Screencast_from_2024-10-09_13-51-32](/uploads/6a046939f5d3bc1550bbcc58bd8546f8/Screencast_from_2024-10-09_13-51-32.mp4)

@jimmac and I have discussed this and I think we agree on the approach. However, it's obviously work. Maybe just making the drag object opaque and adding a light border is enough. :slight_smile:

I vastly prefer to use [Resources](https://apps.gnome.org/Resources/) due to its richer featureset, and it is now a member of GNOME Circle as well.

Tying this extension to `gnome-system-monitor` purely for the fallback icon seems a bit silly, but if changing that is off the table, please indicate that `gnome-system-monitor` is required in the description and/or produce a visible error when it is not installed.

target_title: window-list: Allow rearranging window buttons

note.body:
> That way you would get the drop indication regardless of your Y position

I don't think ignoring the y position altogether is a good idea. In its most extreme form, it means dragging an item onto the top bar has an effect on the bottom bar.

What I did in the latest iteration is add a "proximity threshold", i.e. if the dragged item gets near the window list, it behaves as if it was over the list. It's not pretty (code-wise), but works well enough afaict.

target_title: [places-menu] Places don't fit Nautilus ones

note.body:
Both the extension and nautilus support "Desktop", but they use different conditions:
 - the extension uses the (old traditional) "show-desktop" setting from org.gnome.desktop.background
 - nautilus uses the "desktop_icons" capability from the gtk_shell1 wayland protocol (via GtkSettings)

The nautilus way is more correct, but:
 - it's not available to extensions
 - it's never set on GNOME (because desktop icons are provided
   by an extension, which cannot change the capabilities reported by mutter)

If mutter adds mutter to get/set the capability, then the places-menu extension can use the same condition as nautilus, and the desktop-icons (or ding/ding-gtk4) extension can set it to make it show up in nautilus.

But that's out of scope for this MR.
